How the two licenses map to the code
-------------------------------------
The dual license is intentional, not a generic "pick one". The two licenses
cover different parts of the project:

  * Apache License 2.0 is the license intended for the AMAZON-INTERFACING
    code — the parts that talk to Amazon services / use Amazon product names:
    backend.py (chat with Amazon Q), adapter.py (OpenAI-compatible bridge to
    Q), auth/sso_oidc.py (AWS Builder ID device login), and __init__.py
    (which wraps those). Apache-2.0's NOTICE / attribution and trademark
    clauses are what keep the Amazon / AWS / Amazon Q / Builder ID branding
    boundary explicit and respectful.

  * MIT License is the license intended for the code NOT related to Amazon —
    generic helpers, the dashboard UI shell, tests, and tooling. MIT is the
    simpler, more permissive option for that code.

You may still apply EITHER license to the WHOLE project (that is what
"MIT OR Apache-2.0" means). The split above is the project's INTENDED
mapping, stated so contributors and redistributors are not confused about
which license spirit applies where. Amazon, AWS, Amazon Q, and Builder ID
are trademarks of Amazon.com, Inc.; this project is not affiliated with,
endorsed by, or sponsored by Amazon.
